Something goes wrong when it comes to hashing in a hashmap retrieved from a Json data. The following unit test shows the issue...

```
@Test
public void testHashmap(){

    Map<Integer, Boolean> map = new HashMap<Integer, Boolean>();

    map.put(1, true);
    assertTrue(map.size() == 1);

    map.put(2, false);
    assertTrue(map.size() == 2);

    map.put(1, false);
    assertTrue(map.size() == 2);

    String jsonContent = json.toJson(map);

    map = json.fromJson(HashMap.class, jsonContent);

    assertTrue(map.size() == 2);
            assertTrue(map.keySet().size() == 2);

    map.put(1, false);
            System.out.println(map); //prints: {1=false, 2=false, 1=false}
    assertTrue(map.size() == 2); // AssertionError here
}
```

When disposing the AssetManager, circular dependencies in our assets cause the reference counter of dependencies to decrease too quickly.

This is the code that causes problems with the circular dependency, as you can see, this will loop between assets that depend on each other and eventually crash:

``` java
public synchronized void unload (String fileName) {

    ...

    // get the asset and its type
    Class type = assetTypes.get(fileName);
    if (type == null) throw new GdxRuntimeException("Asset not loaded: " + fileName);

    ...

    // remove any dependencies (or just decrement their ref count).
    Array<String> dependencies = assetDependencies.get(fileName);
    if (dependencies != null) {
        for (String dependency : dependencies) {
            unload(dependency);
        }
    }

    ...
}
```

We patched the problem by adding an if-statement before unloading the dependency:

``` java
public synchronized void unload (String fileName) {

    ...

    // remove any dependencies (or just decrement their ref count).
    Array<String> dependencies = assetDependencies.get(fileName);
    if (dependencies != null) {
        for (String dependency : dependencies) {
            if (isLoaded(dependency)) unload(dependency);
        }
    }

    ...
}
```

This might seem to you like it's just a problem with our assets we need to fix, but it's a little more complicated than that. I'll try to explain:

Our project uses lazy asset references to tackle object serialization problems: when an object (which is loaded in the AssetManager) contains references to other objects (also assets), instead of serializing the asset itself, we serialize a reference to that asset, which can, after all assets have been loaded in the AssetManager, retrieve and internally cache the assets from the AssetManager.

This means that our JsonLoader (an instance of AssetLoader) inspects the object (using the ClassReflection methods) in the getDependencies() stage to see if there are any assets which need to be loaded to make sure the AssetManager loads all of the assets internal asset references. These assets are therefore added as dependency of this object being deserialized. Therefore: when A has a reference to B and B to A, the loading code works fine, but the unloading code crashes. The only way to fix this seems to be stepping away from the automated dependency loading, which would be quite a pain for us.

Are there any ideas/suggestions how we can tackle this problem?

